	url = {https://doi.org/10.1080/01973533.2025.2529512},
	doi = {10.1080/01973533.2025.2529512},
	abstract = {The ability of self-construals, tolerance for ambiguity and social cynicism to explain variations in generalized trust (individuals’ tendency to trust others), was explored in two individualistic, Canada and the USA, and two collectivistic, China and Taiwan, societies. The predictors accounted for a range of explained variance in generalized trust, from 31\% in China to 10\% in Canada. In the USA interdependent self-construal provided the greatest predictability of generalized trust, in Canada and China both interdependent and metapersonal self-construal provided predictability and in Taiwan metapersonal self-construal provided the most predictability. Social cynicism was negatively related to generalized trust in all countries. The results highlight the need to take the relationship between contextual and individual factors into account in understanding generalized trust.},
